{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643346"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18000"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18000"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10714"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64190"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"},{"type":"tags","id":"7304"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27038"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a feature of a typical cervical vertebra?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foramen transversarium only transmits vertebral vein","Gutter-shaped transverse process","Large, kidney-shaped body","Prominent spinous process","Uncinate processes to limit lateral flexion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncinate processes\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of cervical vertebrae and serve to limit lateral flexion, providing stability to the cervical spine. These processes are unique to the cervical region and help in maintaining the alignment of the vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge, kidney-shaped body\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of cervical vertebrae. Cervical vertebrae typically have a small, oval body. The large, kidney-shaped body is more characteristic of lumbar vertebrae, which bear more weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProminent spinous process\u003C/strong\u003E is not typical of cervical vertebrae. Cervical vertebrae have bifid spinous processes, which are less prominent compared to the thoracic vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGutter-shaped transverse process\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of cervical vertebrae. Cervical vertebrae have transverse processes with transverse foramina, which are not gutter-shaped.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eforamen transversarium\u003C/strong\u003E in cervical vertebrae transmits both the vertebral artery and vein, not just the vertebral vein. This is a key feature distinguishing cervical vertebrae from others.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Typical cervical vertebrae have a small body, a bifid spinous process, and transverse foramina.","The transverse foramina in cervical vertebrae transmit the vertebral artery and vein.","Uncinate processes are present in cervical vertebrae to limit lateral flexion."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64190"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18000"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64190"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T21:05:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T21:06:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10714"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78841"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23